INSERT INTO `notes_note` VALUES (2,'Yijie Yuan','2019-11-09 22:46:40.000000','bushberg chapter 12','mp530','bushberg','<!doctype html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n<meta charset=\'UTF-8\'><meta name=\'viewport\' content=\'width=device-width initial-scale=1\'>\r\n<title>bushberg chapter 12(Magnetic Resonance Basics)</title></head>\r\n<body><h3>12.1 Magnetism, Magnetic, and Magnet</h3>\r\n<h4>Magnetism</h4>\r\n<p>Magnetic properties of materials result from the organization and motion of the electrons in either a random or a nonrandom alignment of magnetic “domains,” which are the smallest entities of magnetism.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The SI unit for B is the Tesla (T), An alternate (historical) unit is the gauss (G), where 1 T = 10000 G.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Magnetic Fields</h4>\r\n<p>Nothing to say about it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Magnets</h4>\r\n<p>To be specific, magnets in MR system.</p>\r\n<center><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/YIjieYuan/typora-figurebed/master/img/20191025033126.png\" style=\"zoom: 25%;\"> </center>\r\n<center>Fig1| A cross section of the magnet part</center>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Shim coils: interact with the main magnetic filed to <u>improve homogeneity</u> over the FOV</li>\r\n<li>Radiofrequency(RF) coil: exist within the main bore of the magnet to <u>transmit energy to the patient</u> and to <u>receive returning signals</u>.</li>\r\n<li>Gradient coils: exist within the main bore to produce a <u>linear variation of magnetic field strength</u> across FOV</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Magnetic Properties of Materials</h4>\r\n<p>Magnetic susceptibility describes the extent to which a material becomes magnetized when placed in a magnetic field.</p>\r\n<p>Categories:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><p>diamagnetic</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>e.g. calcium, water, and most organic materials</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><p>paramagnetic</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>e.g. molecular oxygen</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><p>ferromagnetic</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>e.g. iron, cobalt, and nickel</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>	these diamagnetic and paramagnetic agents will <u>deplete or augment</u> the local magnetic field, affecting MR images in known, unknown, and sometimes unexpected ways.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Magnetic Characteristics of the Nucleus</h4>\r\n<p>Magnetic properties result from <u>spin</u> and <u>charge distributoins intrinsic</u> of proton and neutron<sup class=\'md-footnote\'><a href=\'#dfref-footnote-1\' name=\'ref-footnote-1\'>1</a></sup></p>\r\n<p>Magnetic characteristics of the nucleus are described by the <u><em>nuclear magnetic moment</em></u></p>\r\n<p>For a given nucleus, if <u>A is even</u>, the nuclear magnetic moment is 0, else if <u>A is odd</u>, the resultant noninteger nuclear spin generates a nuclear magnetic moment</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Nuclear Magnetic Characteristics of the Elements</h4>\r\n<p>Elements used to produce MR signals: <span class=\"MathJax_SVG\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"font-size: 100%; display: inline-block;\"><svg xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" width=\"3.116ex\" height=\"2.317ex\" viewBox=\"0 -924.6 1341.6 997.6\" role=\"img\" focusable=\"false\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.169ex;\"><defs><path stroke-width=\"0\" id=\"E23-MJMAIN-31\" d=\"M213 578L200 573Q186 568 160 563T102 556H83V602H102Q149 604 189 617T245 641T273 663Q275 666 285 666Q294 666 302 660V361L303 61Q310 54 315 52T339 48T401 46H427V0H416Q395 3 257 3Q121 3 100 0H88V46H114Q136 46 152 46T177 47T193 50T201 52T207 57T213 61V578Z\"></path><path stroke-width=\"0\" id=\"E23-MJMATHI-48\" d=\"M228 637Q194 637 192 641Q191 643 191 649Q191 673 202 682Q204 683 219 683Q260 681 355 681Q389 681 418 681T463 682T483 682Q499 682 499 672Q499 670 497 658Q492 641 487 638H485Q483 638 480 638T473 638T464 637T455 637Q416 636 405 634T387 623Q384 619 355 500Q348 474 340 442T328 395L324 380Q324 378 469 378H614L615 381Q615 384 646 504Q674 619 674 627T617 637Q594 637 587 639T580 648Q580 650 582 660Q5